 and the unknown future. When considered as waiting, the meantime is defined as a period of suspension to be endured. By contrast, the contributors of this volume understand it as a space of “the possible” where calculation coexists with uncertainty, promises with disappointment, and imminence with deferral. Attending to the temporalities of emerging rather than settled facts, they put the stress on the temporal tactics, social commitments, material connections, dispositional orientations, and affective circuits that emerge in the meantime even in the most desperate times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCivilization, Moderny21 century. 0aSocial change. 0aTimexSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology (General), Sociology, Cultural Studies (General).1 aBastian, Misty L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrury, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurham, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurham, Deborah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEriksen, Thomas Hylland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrederiksen, Martin Demant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwon, June Hee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasquelier, Adeline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasquelier, Adeline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcCoy-Torres, Sabia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeiu, George Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Hare, Ann M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat